I should say, good authors strum those chords well and produce melifluously flowing stories. Bad and inexperienced authors snap the chords with too much exposition (in some cases, even if the writin's not necessarily bad), or leave too much slack with a combination of poor writing and quick pacing. Longer stories with sequential arcs can be strung along for ages, but shorter stories don't benefit from that style of writing because it leaves too little meat on the bone for a satisfactory conclusion (unless the ending's interpretation is open-ended, like Channing's "A View From the Fence").

Ruth the Bat benefits from good pacing and writing relative to the kind of story it is and where it's being published.
